WEBVTT

00:21.698 --> 00:28.658
morning on stage, have the best day of your life.

00:56.578 --> 00:57.680
How we doing tonight?

00:57.700 --> 00:58.562
We're doing okay?

00:59.263 --> 01:02.549
Hey, it's great to see you Thanks so much for being here.

01:02.609 --> 01:16.173
It's been an amazing evening already I just have this sense like in my gut like the core of my being that God really wants to do something Here in the room tonight like we're not just here to play Christian games We want to meet with the living God.

01:16.193 --> 01:19.218
We believe that he has spoken through his word and so I am a

01:19.554 --> 01:35.858
So excited that you're here truly and I'm so excited that you're tuning in wherever it is you are if you're tuning in online with us right now like We say this here and you've probably heard me say it before if you tuned in with us But we truly believe like God can meet with anybody anywhere at any time

01:36.066 --> 01:38.189
whenever he so chooses, and that includes you.

01:38.249 --> 01:42.516
So thanks for being a part of what God is doing here at the porch.

01:42.556 --> 01:44.238
We think he has something special in store for you.

01:44.278 --> 01:46.662
Special shout out to all of our porch live locations.

01:46.702 --> 01:53.933
Yeah, we love those guys that are out there across the nation, but particularly porch live Scottsdale in the wonderful state of Arizona.

01:54.374 --> 01:57.919
We love them, porch live Boise, which is awesome.

01:57.939 --> 02:00.703
Things are probably getting cold up north and then porch live Fresno.

02:00.724 --> 02:02.346
We love all of our porch live locations.

02:02.366 --> 02:05.010
So which I'll give it up for them real fast to be amazing.

02:05.826 --> 02:10.292
Well hey, several weeks ago, I got to do something that I thought I never would.

02:10.312 --> 02:13.490
I got to co-pilot a private jet.

02:14.594 --> 02:20.059
Now admittedly, co-pilot is probably a little bit of a strong word because I know nothing about flying an airplane.

02:20.159 --> 02:27.785
And yet, for all intents and purposes, that's essentially what I was doing minus any of the actual control of the aircraft.

02:27.825 --> 02:34.491
Like I was sitting in the cockpit of this plane and I was experiencing everything that the pilot was himself.

02:34.511 --> 02:40.657
Like I'm sitting right there and the plane steering wheel is like coming up through my legs and I can hold on to that thing.

02:40.677 --> 02:44.580
And then there's this dash in front of me and all these meters and lights and different kinds of readings

02:44.560 --> 02:46.402
that I cannot make any kind of sense of it.

02:46.422 --> 02:48.024
They're all right there in front of me.

02:48.064 --> 02:52.068
I got the headphones on so I could hear everything that air traffic control is saying to us.

02:52.128 --> 02:55.271
And I looked to my left and there he is, the pilot himself.

02:55.291 --> 02:57.153
Like this thing was awesome.

02:57.193 --> 02:59.236
I'd never experienced anything like it.

02:59.276 --> 03:02.920
And yet the reason it was so great wasn't just because I'd never been on a plane before.

03:02.940 --> 03:03.921
I'd been on a plane before.

03:03.981 --> 03:07.124
Like I've ridden on the big commercial airplanes.

03:07.264 --> 03:07.845
I grew up.

03:07.885 --> 03:10.848
My granddad, he flew a little prop plane.

03:10.888 --> 03:13.030
And so I'd been in that sort of situation before.

03:13.311 --> 03:14.532
But I had never been

03:14.512 --> 03:16.655
in the cockpit of a private jet.

03:16.675 --> 03:22.804
And so being in that environment changed everything for me because the views are a little bit different from up there.

03:22.844 --> 03:23.444
You know what I'm saying?

03:23.464 --> 03:25.668
Like I'm sitting there and I'm not looking out the side view mirror.

03:26.088 --> 03:30.234
I'm looking out the front windshield and I'm seeing everything that's happening.

03:30.254 --> 03:36.082
And so we're sitting there and we pull out onto the runway and we kind of line up and

03:36.194 --> 03:38.396
We get clearance from air traffic control to go for it.

03:38.416 --> 03:43.540
And so next thing you know, we're like a bullet, like racing down this runway and the lines in front of us are speeding by.

03:43.560 --> 03:46.643
And this jet is, it is accelerating so fast.

03:46.683 --> 03:47.684
It was the coolest experience.

03:47.704 --> 03:50.386
And next thing you know, he gently lifts us off the ground.

03:50.747 --> 03:53.289
It was the moment I'd been waiting for.

03:53.329 --> 03:57.613
And as we do, like rain kind of begins to pelt our windshield because it was sort of a dreary day.

03:57.633 --> 04:00.015
And next thing you know, we get up into the clouds.

04:00.055 --> 04:05.039
And it's kind of a disorienting experience because we're in these clouds and we can't see anything.

04:05.099 --> 04:06.180
All we can see is the rain.

04:06.160 --> 04:12.967
on the front windshield until we broke through the clouds and we reached our cruising altitude.

04:13.308 --> 04:23.399
And as we went from a pitched ascent to a flattened cruising altitude, we found ourselves facing the most beautiful of settings.

04:23.419 --> 04:26.442
I mean, this was the closest to heaven that I'd ever seen before, you know what I'm saying?

04:26.922 --> 04:30.386
I am looking at white clouds beneath us

04:30.498 --> 04:33.000
kind of billowing across like bubble wrap.

04:33.020 --> 04:39.606
And then as you're looking around, you can see out over to my right this massive storm cell and lightning cracking within it.

04:39.626 --> 04:43.029
And then as I look over to my left, you can see blue where there was no blue before.

04:43.049 --> 04:46.072
Like this was the most amazing kind of scene.

04:46.092 --> 04:53.558
And as I'm sitting there and I'm taking it all in, I start to pepper the pilot with my personal list of 20 questions because this is the closest thing to flying I'm ever gonna get.

04:53.578 --> 04:55.760
And so I've got a bunch of things that I want to figure out.

04:56.060 --> 05:00.484
And as he's answering all of them, he said something that really stuck with me so much so

05:00.464 --> 05:03.428
I wrote it down on my notes because I wanted to make sure I could share it with you.

05:03.488 --> 05:08.416
He said, from the ground, it feels like the weather is always changing.

05:09.437 --> 05:13.203
But from up here, we know the sun is always shining.

05:14.184 --> 05:17.970
And as he said that at 30,000 feet, I thought of you, porch.

05:18.434 --> 05:24.079
You were on my mind as I flew in the cockpit of this plane because I thought that's not just true to pilots.

05:24.399 --> 05:26.381
That's true to you and me.

05:26.401 --> 05:30.304
Like from many of you here, it feels like the weather in your world is always changing.

05:30.324 --> 05:33.047
Like one minute, the weather might be beautiful.

05:33.087 --> 05:37.651
And the next thing you know, it feels like a storm is shaking your reality.

05:37.671 --> 05:44.937
And then you're next slipping into this sort of apathetic sort of moody gray weather weather sort of situation.

05:45.257 --> 05:48.420
And yet though the weather may always feel like it's changing,

05:48.400 --> 05:53.928
in your world, you can be confident that the sun is still shining.

05:55.751 --> 05:58.275
It all depends on your perspective, however.

05:59.256 --> 06:01.840
That's how you're able to discern the difference.

06:01.900 --> 06:08.550
Like that pilot, you've got to get up to an altitude where you can see things as they actually are.

06:08.651 --> 06:11.194
You've got to get up to God's altitude.

06:11.214 --> 06:13.618
You've got to see from his perspective

06:14.050 --> 06:19.570
And as you do, you're able to make sense of whatever it is you're truly feeling in life.

06:20.866 --> 06:22.728
That's what we've been trying to do in this series.

06:22.768 --> 06:29.453
Like if you're here for the very first time, we've been journey through a series called 2020 where we're trying to put your mental health into perspective.

06:29.473 --> 06:32.356
And the way that we've been doing it is we've been doing it through the book of Psalms.

06:32.776 --> 06:39.963
The reason why we've been in the book of Psalms is, the book of Psalms is sort of, it reads kind of like your personal diary.

06:40.003 --> 06:42.164
Not that you have a personal diary, but maybe you had a personal diary.

06:42.184 --> 06:43.546
It reads like that though.

06:43.566 --> 06:49.491
It's full of raw emotion, brutal honesty, like impassioned pleas.

06:49.531 --> 06:50.852
That's the way the Psalms

06:50.832 --> 06:52.054
read out.

06:52.074 --> 06:56.921
It's like your diary in the sense that it is 100% full of emotion.

06:57.682 --> 07:04.431
And yet the Psalms is unlike your diary in that it is also 100% full of truth.

07:05.032 --> 07:20.274
That's why it's the perfect place to process a proper perspective when it comes to our mental and emotional health because we can feel all of our feelings and yet we can bring those things as the psalmist do to God's truth.

07:20.834 --> 07:27.421
and he can speak into them, inform them, and ultimately shape the way that we walk through this world.

07:28.422 --> 07:38.892
And so what we're doing over the course of the series is we're really framing around the top five mental health challenges, most common amongst Americans today.

07:38.952 --> 07:48.402
The first week was all about depression, the second week was all about anxiety, and tonight we're gonna be talking about addiction, addiction and indulgence.

07:48.898 --> 07:52.341
And to unpack it, we're gonna be looking at Psalm 141.

07:52.802 --> 07:54.643
So if you've got a Bible, you can turn with me there.

07:54.703 --> 08:01.590
Psalm 141, while you're doing that, let me just say this because it's important to be said week after week.

08:02.831 --> 08:04.012
We know our depth up here.

08:04.092 --> 08:09.157
Like I'm not a doctor, there's no part of me that is trying to diagnose what it is you're dealing with.

08:09.197 --> 08:18.546
Like I feel very comfortable and confident from the scripture to speak into a variety of situational sorts of circumstances.

08:18.658 --> 08:24.765
Many of you here, you may find yourself beyond the bounds of a situational type of mental health challenge.

08:24.805 --> 08:26.306
You might be facing something that is clinical.

08:26.667 --> 08:32.373
Instead, if that's you, what I want you to know is the truth of God's word will be vital for your healing.

08:33.855 --> 08:44.146
But that doesn't mean it's mutually exclusive to the treatment plan or recommendations made by your doctor, like the scripture and your prescription.

08:44.546 --> 08:46.569
they can work in partnership together.

08:46.589 --> 08:49.653
They can be a part of your healing journey.

08:49.993 --> 09:12.603
And I also want to say that if you're here tonight and you would consider yourself an addict, maybe you've been diagnosed as such or maybe yourself diagnosed as such, I just want you to hear, nowhere in this message are you going to hear me say, you just need to stop that because that would imply that you have the strength to overcome your addiction all on your own.

09:13.505 --> 09:14.546
And the truth is,

09:15.074 --> 09:17.639
Many addicts do not have the strength to do that.

09:17.820 --> 09:20.505
Instead, they need to rely on the strength of others.

09:20.566 --> 09:22.750
And so I want to stand before you right now.

09:23.291 --> 09:26.438
And if that's you, I just want to plead with you.

09:27.360 --> 09:30.226
Would you let us be strong for you?

09:30.658 --> 09:37.585
Would you give us the permission to jump into whatever it is you're dealing with by visiting with us at the end of the night?

09:37.625 --> 09:39.827
You don't have to necessarily come down front.

09:39.848 --> 09:56.465
You can find anybody in a black shirt and a lanyard and you can just grab them by the hand and they'll know like, okay, that means that I probably need to visit with you and private pull you over and introduce you to someone on staff, but we're really serious about helping you make good strides when it comes to the topic of your addiction.

09:56.485 --> 09:57.746
Now, with all of that said,

09:58.178 --> 10:02.403
How do we get a proper perspective on addiction, on indulgence?

10:02.423 --> 10:05.306
Well, first and foremost, we have to understand the problem of it.

10:05.326 --> 10:07.188
That's where we've begun all of these talks.

10:07.208 --> 10:08.510
That's where we're beginning here tonight.

10:08.810 --> 10:13.395
We need to understand that addiction is a bigger deal in danger than most of us realize.

10:13.796 --> 10:23.186
So if you've been tracking the headlines and you may already know this, but in case you haven't, we are, according to many researchers facing what they're calling an addiction crisis.

10:23.874 --> 10:29.183
According to Shatterproof, one of the leading nonprofit organizations that's committed to ending addiction in our country.

10:29.244 --> 10:29.604
Hear this.

10:29.985 --> 10:40.964
Nearly 49 million Americans, I repeat, nearly 49 million Americans ages 12 or older had a substance use addiction in the past year.

10:41.846 --> 10:44.210
Meaning they rely on things like

10:44.322 --> 10:55.320
like alcohol and cannabis and cocaine and methamphetamine and opioids, they rely on all manner of different substances to provide them the kind of comfort they cannot find elsewhere.

10:55.861 --> 11:06.258
To put that into perspective for you, because 49 million may feel a little bit ethereal, that means nearly one in six people are living in substance dependence today.

11:06.946 --> 11:14.414
Making it likely that you and I will encounter someone that either has or will have some sort of substance use disorder in their life.

11:15.155 --> 11:18.659
Now you may be sitting here and thinking to yourself, but Kyle and I don't struggle with that.

11:19.239 --> 11:21.342
So this doesn't feel relevant to me at all.

11:21.362 --> 11:32.894
Well, before you tune me out, that's only half of what we're discussing tonight because what you need to also know is that while there is substance use addiction, there's also something else called behavioral addiction.

11:33.515 --> 11:36.338
Track with me here because this one's far more prevalent.

11:36.802 --> 11:43.208
Behavioral addiction is like substance addiction, except it's not being addicted to drugs or alcohol.

11:43.669 --> 11:53.838
Instead, the individual is addicted to a particular behavior in the feelings that are evoked from that behavior that lead them to a place where they lack self-control.

11:54.899 --> 11:57.562
So see if you identify potentially.

11:57.602 --> 12:05.970
Behavioral addiction can include things like social media, pornography, cell phone use, video gaming, workaholism, food,

12:06.146 --> 12:08.829
Compulsive shopping, exercise, who would have thought?

12:08.929 --> 12:10.972
Self-harm and gambling.

12:11.833 --> 12:15.457
All of these things can be damaging to your mental health.

12:15.477 --> 12:16.919
Now, why do I share all that with you?

12:17.159 --> 12:20.163
Some of you are sitting here like, dude, just get into Psalm 141.

12:20.663 --> 12:21.324
We're going to.

12:21.444 --> 12:22.285
Just bear with me.

12:22.946 --> 12:33.138
It's important for us to understand this warning that none of us are as safe as we think we are when it comes to the topic of addiction.

12:33.762 --> 12:39.528
Do you think anybody ever intends to enslave themselves to some sort of indulgence?

12:40.689 --> 12:42.370
No, of course they don't.

12:42.831 --> 12:44.172
Nobody is ever intending.

12:44.192 --> 12:44.633
You know what?

12:44.693 --> 12:46.154
I do think I'll be an alcoholic.

12:46.174 --> 12:47.435
That sounds like a nice way of living.

12:47.455 --> 12:48.817
Nobody is intending to do that.

12:49.037 --> 12:57.345
And we laugh, and yet the reality is this thing comes for all of us in a way where it doesn't just suddenly show up instead it gradually creeps in.

12:57.946 --> 13:02.450
It's like the free app on your phone that you downloaded because, ah,

13:02.882 --> 13:06.067
Nothing's harmless and yet it's draining your battery.

13:06.948 --> 13:07.970
It's stealing your data.

13:08.611 --> 13:10.133
It's waking you up at two in the morning.

13:10.193 --> 13:11.215
Like that's what's happening.

13:11.235 --> 13:13.999
It's creeped into your life under the premise.

13:14.019 --> 13:19.909
It is harmless and yet it's actually come to disrupt everything about your reality.

13:21.311 --> 13:23.314
And so we've got to know what do we do with it?

13:23.714 --> 13:33.527
Like how do we actually move away from what we're going to get to that, but what we have to understand first and foremost and David actually shares this with us is an addiction.

13:33.887 --> 13:37.552
It takes root because it appeals to your reward system.

13:38.333 --> 13:41.437
A really simple way of understanding that is it feels good to be bad.

13:41.497 --> 13:43.380
That's what happens.

13:43.900 --> 13:45.202
So think of it like this.

13:46.018 --> 13:52.448
Not everyone that drinks doom scrolls and watches pornography does it because they just want to be a really addicted individual.

13:52.488 --> 13:57.596
No, they do it because they're trying to reduce stress, loneliness, discomfort.

13:58.637 --> 14:12.178
A lot of people that work in high stress, fast paced corporate environments, they will find themselves using things like alcohol and prescription medication and stimulants because they want to

14:12.290 --> 14:15.694
because they ultimately know what it takes to keep up in this environment.

14:15.714 --> 14:18.137
They're not doing it because, well, that's going to make mom proud.

14:18.397 --> 14:23.422
Instead, they're doing it because that's the price they have to pay to be productive.

14:24.364 --> 14:25.665
Any procrastinators in the room?

14:26.586 --> 14:28.088
Why are you a procrastinator?

14:28.428 --> 14:30.811
Is it just because you want everybody to be waiting on you?

14:30.831 --> 14:31.311
No.

14:31.892 --> 14:33.914
Is it because you love to watch the world burn?

14:34.255 --> 14:34.615
Some of you.

14:34.895 --> 14:40.882
But really, the reason so many of you are procrastinators is because you're a perfectionist.

14:41.538 --> 14:50.712
And so you're trying to reduce the anxiety and the frustrations you feel about completing a task that is less than the standard you actually want to achieve.

14:50.972 --> 14:51.733
Do you see how it works?

14:52.815 --> 14:57.182
It feels good, leaves you rewarded to do bad.

14:58.263 --> 15:01.388
And we see David wrestling with that very reality in Psalm 141.

15:01.588 --> 15:06.415
Now, as we set this passage up, what you need to know is the context of it is debated.

15:06.996 --> 15:08.178
We don't necessarily know

15:08.290 --> 15:10.975
for certain what the situation around David is.

15:10.995 --> 15:18.207
And yet as we read through it, you can sort of pick out some context clues to help you guess where he may be and what may be happening.

15:19.329 --> 15:21.031
Scholars, they land in one of two places.

15:21.492 --> 15:29.746
They either think that he is being pursued by King Saul in his youth or King Absalom following his kingship.

15:30.178 --> 15:38.406
And what you need to know is neither one of them ultimately really matter because what we can understand is they are both marked by a similar set of circumstances.

15:39.107 --> 15:40.588
The guy's being hunted down.

15:41.709 --> 15:42.970
Tough day at the office, right?

15:42.991 --> 15:44.252
Like he's being hunted down.

15:44.492 --> 15:46.714
He's being pursued by attackers.

15:46.754 --> 15:48.596
His life is on the line.

15:48.816 --> 15:56.344
And so what we see him say in the middle of that entire situation in verse three, he says, set a guard, O Lord, over my mouth.

15:56.924 --> 15:58.866
Keep watch over the door of my lips.

15:59.266 --> 16:06.902
Do not let my heart incline to any evil to busy myself with wicked deeds and company with men who work iniquity and let me not eat of their delicacies.

16:08.004 --> 16:09.226
Do you hear the struggle in his voice?

16:10.228 --> 16:14.477
What David is saying right here is he saying, I want to sin.

16:14.497 --> 16:16.882
Like I want to get back.

16:17.378 --> 16:21.343
I want to dish back whatever has been dished out to me.

16:21.564 --> 16:23.867
Like I want to give them a dose of their own medicine.

16:23.887 --> 16:25.890
They're trying to pursue me and take me out.

16:25.950 --> 16:27.912
I want to pursue them and I want to take them out.

16:27.932 --> 16:28.994
God, that's what I want to do.

16:29.294 --> 16:32.058
I'm praying to you because I actually want to sin.

16:32.278 --> 16:34.882
And so God, what I'm asking is that you would guard me from myself.

16:34.922 --> 16:36.304
That's what he's articulating right here.

16:37.205 --> 16:40.950
The problem of his indulgence is he wants to retaliate.

16:41.250 --> 16:46.898
He wants to indulge an evil desire against those that have been evil against him.

16:47.586 --> 16:51.229
And the way that he says, God, would you guard me is threefold.

16:51.250 --> 16:53.231
He asks God, would you guard my mouth?

16:53.291 --> 16:54.332
Would you guard my heart?

16:54.393 --> 16:56.675
And would you guard my desire?

16:57.335 --> 16:58.556
Why is it threefold?

16:59.798 --> 17:01.159
Because that's the way it works.

17:01.219 --> 17:03.621
Remember, indulgence creeps in.

17:04.382 --> 17:05.483
It doesn't just show up.

17:06.444 --> 17:08.566
It gradually takes hold.

17:09.167 --> 17:10.868
And so it often begins with our words.

17:11.369 --> 17:15.353
He says, keep watch over the door of my lips.

17:15.893 --> 17:16.914
Why does he start there?

17:17.378 --> 17:31.211
Watch over my mouth, God, because what we say out loud, what we feel inside is giving our feelings and opportunity to become a legitimized to the point that we identify with them.

17:32.032 --> 17:33.293
So I'll give you an example of this.

17:33.954 --> 17:37.417
I thought it was fascinating a year ago during the Paris Olympics.

17:38.598 --> 17:42.222
Olympians were regularly asked by reporters, are you nervous?

17:42.802 --> 17:46.706
And they would regularly reply, no, I'm excited.

17:47.298 --> 17:56.930
which is fascinating why, because both nervousness and excitement are similar in terms of the physical sensation they produce.

17:58.031 --> 18:05.401
Gives you clammy hands and a sweaty brow and a racing heart, like that's what ultimately nervousness and excitement both do.

18:05.941 --> 18:13.571
And yet what these Olympians are saying is that they want to positively identify with that emotion as opposed to negatively identify with that emotion.

18:14.052 --> 18:15.954
So they're not willing to,

18:16.194 --> 18:18.261
Subscribe to the way the reporter is saying it.

18:18.301 --> 18:22.094
Instead, they want to reframe it so they identify with it instead.

18:22.456 --> 18:25.366
They know what I say is what I'm going to become.

18:25.647 --> 18:26.891
And so I don't want to be nervous.

18:27.132 --> 18:28.055
I want to be excited.

18:28.135 --> 18:28.978
Makes sense.

18:29.090 --> 18:31.072
That's why you have to start with your words.

18:31.473 --> 18:35.858
David is saying in reference to something similar we see in the book of James.

18:36.119 --> 18:37.640
We're not going to read this specific passage.

18:37.660 --> 18:43.408
You can go look at his James 3, 3, 3, 5, but we learn that the power of the tongue is extreme.

18:43.828 --> 18:46.151
It's like a bit in the mouth of a horse.

18:46.431 --> 18:48.334
It's like a rudder on the tail of a ship.

18:48.594 --> 18:50.937
It's like a fire that can set the whole forest ablaze.

18:51.117 --> 18:55.863
Like it has great power to change the whole of something.

18:56.423 --> 18:58.546
So too does your mouth have that kind of power.

18:59.586 --> 19:00.387
but it doesn't stop there.

19:01.088 --> 19:03.552
It doesn't just affect your words, it affects your deeds.

19:04.133 --> 19:07.158
He says, do not let my heart incline to any evil.

19:08.700 --> 19:15.411
In the West, when we read the word heart, we think Valentine's Day and the things that I feel, butterflies inside, love for other people.

19:15.471 --> 19:17.153
You know, like we think it's all about emotion.

19:17.193 --> 19:23.323
And yet what we know is the heart in the ancient Near Eastern mind is not about emotion as much as it is about action.

19:24.064 --> 19:25.426
It's the seed of the will.

19:26.210 --> 19:30.796
which is basically the place from which you make decisions in life.

19:31.357 --> 19:40.249
And so David is saying here, he's like, hey, I don't just feel temptation to slander my enemies, to use my mouth, to tear them down.

19:40.830 --> 19:47.099
I also feel the urge to retaliate against him, to take swift action, to dish back what they've dished to me.

19:48.341 --> 19:49.362
But he doesn't just stop there.

19:50.403 --> 19:55.250
Begins with his words, it moves to his deeds, and then it creeps into his desire.

19:55.778 --> 19:59.022
He says, let me not eat of their delicacies.

20:00.543 --> 20:05.188
It's a really important part of the verse because it tells us something important about the way that sin works.

20:06.370 --> 20:09.393
Sin doesn't just want you to do evil.

20:10.594 --> 20:12.597
Sin wants you to delight in evil.

20:13.798 --> 20:14.899
It wants you to love it.

20:15.860 --> 20:20.365
That's why it feels bad or it feels good to do something bad.

20:20.886 --> 20:24.690
Remember, ultimately, it wants to appeal to your

20:24.770 --> 20:25.771
pleasure.

20:26.231 --> 20:27.312
It's a delicacy.

20:27.413 --> 20:38.043
It's a delight to the taste, which is really important because it teaches us something we need to understand about indulgence or temptation or addiction ultimately.

20:38.463 --> 20:41.967
We need to know it's rarely about the substance.

20:43.969 --> 20:46.171
Instead, it's about what the substance represents.

20:47.993 --> 20:53.458
What I mean by that is David was not just

20:53.538 --> 20:55.421
intent to take these guys out.

20:57.003 --> 21:05.294
He was willing to do that if it afforded him peace from his anxiety, freedom from their pursuit, in hope of a brand new future.

21:05.354 --> 21:06.015
See how that works.

21:06.736 --> 21:08.138
He's not just focused on the substance.

21:09.039 --> 21:10.621
He's focused on what the substance represents.

21:11.262 --> 21:14.266
And that's the way it works for everybody.

21:15.007 --> 21:22.898
Like whether it's behavioral or it is substance, pornography, excessive shopping,

21:23.522 --> 21:29.310
eating disorders, opioid addiction, it doesn't matter, across the range of it all.

21:29.891 --> 21:32.455
It's never about the substance, about what the substance represents.

21:32.515 --> 21:33.677
Oh, well, that gives me relief.

21:34.298 --> 21:35.640
Well, that provides me comfortable.

21:35.680 --> 21:38.864
I feel a sense of belonging whenever I do that.

21:38.884 --> 21:43.251
I get freedom whenever I find myself actually participating in that activity.

21:43.371 --> 21:44.412
I get validation.

21:44.533 --> 21:46.015
I matter whenever I do that.

21:46.055 --> 21:46.776
See how it works?

21:49.139 --> 21:50.962
But what if I could, what if I told you?

21:51.618 --> 21:54.422
You could find all of that and more without the substance.

21:55.643 --> 22:00.610
What if I told you there was a way to feel good by doing good?

22:02.372 --> 22:04.995
What if I told you there was a way to change your perspective altogether?

22:06.537 --> 22:09.862
Well, that's what the rest of Psalm 141 is all about.

22:10.863 --> 22:16.971
And that's what we're going to talk about because if your problem is indulgence, your perspective can be self-control.

22:18.292 --> 22:19.474
Just like David says,

22:20.482 --> 22:26.170
And to show you how that happens, I'm going to give you four ways to control your cravings moving forward.

22:27.251 --> 22:28.072
And let me be very clear.

22:28.112 --> 22:36.163
This is for the addict in the room, but this is for all of us in the room because it never begins at addiction.

22:36.884 --> 22:39.568
It starts at temptation and we have to deal with that.

22:40.148 --> 22:40.729
So here we go.

22:41.170 --> 22:47.378
Verse one, starting at the beginning of the passage, says, Oh Lord, I call upon you, hasten to me.

22:47.458 --> 22:49.140
Give ear to my voice when I call to you.

22:49.360 --> 22:54.245
Let my prayer be counted as incense before you in the lifting up of my hands as the evening sacrifice.

22:54.806 --> 23:01.492
So the first thing you need to know if you want to control your cravings is you pray before you do anything else.

23:02.934 --> 23:08.960
You pray before you do anything else, which probably feels classically Christian to you.

23:09.561 --> 23:11.182
You're like, you should pray first.

23:12.003 --> 23:14.706
What a typical recommendation from the pastor.

23:15.714 --> 23:25.746
Just bear with me for a minute because I understand you're probably sitting there thinking like okay, like I'll write this one down But I'm really interested in whatever he's gonna say next but this one matters because it sets up everything from here

23:25.922 --> 23:27.684
Like it's not just that he's praying.

23:27.804 --> 23:31.849
Yes, you need to know what he's doing, but you need to know how he's doing it.

23:31.929 --> 23:32.730
How does he do it?

23:32.790 --> 23:39.198
If you read it, it says he hastens, he offers like incense, he calls, he lifts his hands.

23:39.218 --> 23:39.819
Do you see that?

23:40.079 --> 23:45.045
Like there's an earnestness, there's a seriousness, there's an urgency, there's an intensity to the way that he's praying.

23:45.285 --> 23:52.434
He is looking at his situation and he's not thinking to himself, this is the first step in the Christian formula for self-control.

23:52.802 --> 23:54.066
No, he's not doing that.

23:54.367 --> 23:57.957
He's looking at it and he is making a 911 call to heaven.

23:58.419 --> 24:02.290
He is dialing up God and he is saying, I need help.

24:02.594 --> 24:09.485
Like I'm facing something that is ultimately alluring to me and alluring of me is something that I don't want to do.

24:09.846 --> 24:12.991
Like God, I'm being chased down and I'm tired of it.

24:13.211 --> 24:15.354
Like I want to indulge the evil desire I have.

24:15.635 --> 24:18.099
I want to give into the negative attitude that I'm feeling.

24:18.359 --> 24:20.302
God, I need you to help me.

24:20.643 --> 24:24.729
He knows the temptation he's facing is so strong.

24:26.172 --> 24:30.258
And so he prays because God is stronger.

24:31.938 --> 24:33.240
That's why you pray.

24:33.280 --> 24:37.066
You realize, I'm not strong enough.

24:38.448 --> 24:39.349
God is instead.

24:41.152 --> 24:42.053
That's where he starts.

24:42.554 --> 24:43.916
He starts by coming to God.

24:44.557 --> 24:50.346
So let me ask you, when you face temptation, where do you turn first?

24:52.289 --> 24:57.397
Like whenever you sense yourself tempted with sexual desire, do you turn to God first?

24:58.318 --> 25:01.042
Or do you turn to your explore page?

25:01.954 --> 25:04.097
And just start scrolling because, well, man, that's not porn.

25:05.278 --> 25:07.941
When in reality, it's just a slippery slope.

25:08.522 --> 25:11.986
It's going to move you right into that, which you want to avoid.

25:12.587 --> 25:18.054
Like whenever you feel in yourself, a temptation to just numb out, like, do you turn first to God?

25:19.095 --> 25:21.639
Or do you turn to some kind of mindless entertainment?

25:22.640 --> 25:27.666
Scrolling, shopping, eating, gaming, whatever it may be.

25:29.154 --> 25:32.258
Maybe it's not that, maybe whenever you're tempted by insecurity.

25:33.920 --> 25:44.113
Do you turn first to God or do you turn to admit how much money am I actually making or what kind of body am I actually building or how many followers am I accumulating?

25:44.133 --> 25:45.194
Like what is it for you?

25:45.234 --> 25:47.197
It could be any manner of things.

25:47.217 --> 25:48.238
There's just three examples.

25:48.258 --> 25:53.524
There are so many more examples that I could give, but the point nevertheless remains.

25:54.065 --> 25:57.970
If you're turning some other place than God, you are turning to the wrong place.

25:58.722 --> 26:00.104
And I want to love you enough to just say that.

26:00.965 --> 26:08.277
There's no other place where you will find the strength to overcome your temptation than if you turn first and foremost to God.

26:09.238 --> 26:09.919
How do I know that?

26:10.720 --> 26:12.243
Because that's what Jesus said.

26:13.505 --> 26:20.015
He taught this to his own disciples in that moment of greatest temptation in the Garden of Gethsemane.

26:20.035 --> 26:27.346
He looked at Peter, James, and John, and he said this in Matthew 2641, he said, watch and pray.

26:28.098 --> 26:30.401
that you may not enter into temptation.

26:31.021 --> 26:35.026
The spirit indeed is willing, but the flesh is weak.

26:36.548 --> 26:39.191
Doesn't that just resonate with so many of you?

26:39.251 --> 26:40.953
That resonates with me.

26:41.634 --> 26:42.896
Like, watch and pray why.

26:44.237 --> 26:45.178
The spirit is willing.

26:45.939 --> 26:49.343
Like, I don't want to sin God, but the flesh is weak.

26:49.964 --> 26:51.666
You don't have the strength.

26:52.194 --> 26:53.756
to make it through this temptation.

26:54.176 --> 26:59.402
But if you seek God, therein you'll find the strength you need for your deliverance.

26:59.422 --> 27:01.885
That's the first thing you gotta know, but you gotta come to him.

27:05.849 --> 27:10.334
Let me ask you, I wasn't playing on saying this, but I think it's important.

27:12.576 --> 27:19.524
What if you prayed as hard before the sin as you pray after the sin?

27:20.665 --> 27:21.746
What would that look like?

27:22.370 --> 27:28.356
What would it look like for you to labor and prayer before as opposed to seek forgiveness following?

27:29.237 --> 27:31.420
I bet that would look radically different for so many of us.

27:31.720 --> 27:32.701
And listen, I get it.

27:32.861 --> 27:35.124
Some of you are sitting here like, try that, doesn't work.

27:35.424 --> 27:37.026
Listen, I've tried that, didn't work.

27:37.046 --> 27:38.027
You wanna know why it didn't work?

27:38.207 --> 27:39.829
Because I put up a haphazard prayer.

27:41.010 --> 27:42.832
It wasn't that God didn't show up after I prayed.

27:43.192 --> 27:44.354
I didn't show up when I prayed.

27:45.174 --> 27:46.496
I was like, God, this is gonna be a tempting moment.

27:46.516 --> 27:47.577
Would you please meet me in it?

27:47.737 --> 27:48.938
Please deliver me, Lord, I love you.

27:50.480 --> 27:52.242
And it made no difference, why?

27:52.706 --> 27:55.429
because I wasn't really looking for a difference.

27:55.449 --> 27:57.271
I wasn't really seeking God.

27:58.793 --> 28:05.600
What would it look like for you to pray with the kind of earnestness and seriousness that David did?

28:06.301 --> 28:11.626
And listen, I'm not saying prayers easy, but what I am saying is sometimes you gotta pray until you pray.

28:12.587 --> 28:16.912
That's an old Puritan expression, and I think it is so true to so many of us.

28:17.132 --> 28:18.734
Like, what does prayer do?

28:18.914 --> 28:22.578
It's not getting God on board with your agenda, it's you getting on board with God's agenda.

28:22.978 --> 28:27.664
And so sometimes if your heart feels cold, the first place you need to go is you just need to start praying to them.

28:27.684 --> 28:36.395
Like that's where you need, you need to go into the closet and you need to hit your knees and you need to start lifting up words and you need to trust the fact that they're not just rebounding off the ceiling.

28:36.595 --> 28:40.960
They're somehow by God's grace, making their way all the way to heaven's throne.

28:41.021 --> 28:42.683
That's what's happening in that moment.

28:43.484 --> 28:44.485
It's supernatural.

28:44.905 --> 28:47.128
It's the most supernatural of spiritual disciplines.

28:49.551 --> 28:50.252
What would it look like?

28:50.793 --> 28:51.794
You feel like you have

28:53.282 --> 28:55.084
No power in the face of your sin.

28:55.104 --> 28:56.627
You want to know where powerlessness comes from?

28:56.687 --> 28:57.728
It comes from prayerlessness.

28:59.591 --> 29:00.151
So you pray.

29:00.692 --> 29:02.414
You pray before you do anything else.

29:02.434 --> 29:03.155
You've got to come do them.

29:03.175 --> 29:03.856
That's the first thing.

29:04.337 --> 29:04.898
Let's keep going.

29:06.640 --> 29:07.622
We're going to go back to verse three.

29:08.983 --> 29:10.586
He says, Set a guard, O Lord, over my mouth.

29:10.966 --> 29:12.248
Keep watch over the door of my lips.

29:12.668 --> 29:17.215
Do not let my heart incline to any evil to busy myself with wicked deeds and the company with men who work iniquity.

29:18.216 --> 29:19.698
And let me not eat of their delicacies.

29:20.258 --> 29:26.304
The second thing you need to know if you want to control your cravings is don't justify bad decisions.

29:27.986 --> 29:29.447
Don't justify bad decisions.

29:30.168 --> 29:30.488
I love it.

29:30.508 --> 29:31.609
We already looked at these verses.

29:31.669 --> 29:41.699
David is literally saying in this moment, like, I want to sin and yet the amazing thing is in the face of his desire, he does not make up any justification.

29:42.560 --> 29:45.743
He doesn't look at God and be like, oh God, yeah, you remember that guy Goliath?

29:46.584 --> 29:48.786
Yeah, I was there for that one.

29:48.930 --> 29:51.473
No one else was willing to do it, but I stepped up and I did it.

29:51.493 --> 29:52.635
You owe me this, God.

29:52.855 --> 29:54.538
He doesn't come up with that kind of excuse.

29:55.078 --> 29:57.281
He doesn't look at God and say, uh, did you forget?

29:57.301 --> 29:58.823
Like you were the one that anointed me.

29:58.863 --> 30:02.849
Like I didn't ask for this, but you chose me to be the king of Israel.

30:03.029 --> 30:04.190
And now I'm out here in the wilderness.

30:04.210 --> 30:05.532
I'm running for my life.

30:05.893 --> 30:07.855
What's it going to look like for you to help me out for once?

30:08.076 --> 30:10.379
He doesn't come up with all of these justifications and excuses.

30:10.759 --> 30:11.741
I love that he doesn't.

30:12.021 --> 30:15.506
And yet I'm also convicted by the reality that we do this all the time.

30:16.287 --> 30:18.770
We do come up with justifications for our sin.

30:19.170 --> 30:24.519
Like we don't just, like we do, we give ourselves way too much credit.

30:25.601 --> 30:28.986
We'll say things like, well, I deserve this God.

30:29.006 --> 30:30.248
You know how hard I've been working?

30:31.090 --> 30:32.292
How fast I've been going?

30:32.632 --> 30:34.034
Like everybody needs something for me.

30:34.075 --> 30:35.357
What about what I need God?

30:35.677 --> 30:36.799
Like I need a break.

30:37.640 --> 30:38.642
I need a breath.

30:39.266 --> 30:42.649
I need to catch an hour all to myself, God, I need this.

30:42.809 --> 30:43.851
I deserve this.

30:43.971 --> 30:45.092
I've earned this.

30:45.212 --> 30:47.014
I've worked hard for this, God.

30:47.154 --> 30:49.136
I deserve whatever it is that I'm craving.

30:49.876 --> 30:50.657
Maybe it's not that.

30:51.638 --> 30:55.282
Maybe it's, but this is only going to happen once.

30:57.584 --> 31:02.989
It's just one drink, but God, my birthday, one comes around one time a year.

31:04.751 --> 31:05.492
I've been saving up.

31:05.572 --> 31:07.794
It's time to spend a little bit on myself.

31:09.698 --> 31:34.706
my friends like we haven't gotten together in forever and this is the one time we're all going to get together and so just this once like I'm gonna bend the rules a little bit I might make some compromising decisions who knows like we might get a little crazy maybe it's not that maybe instead it's well who's it gonna hurt like who's it gonna hurt for me to stay up all night watching TV like no one staying up and being impacted that by that but me or who's it gonna hurt if I if I

31:34.786 --> 31:37.789
make sexual advances via some sort of dating app.

31:37.809 --> 31:39.891
Like, I don't know them, they don't know me, and who knows?

31:39.931 --> 31:41.512
Like, maybe I'll hit one and it'll go well.

31:42.153 --> 31:42.994
Maybe it's not that.

31:43.474 --> 31:44.775
Like, maybe it's my body.

31:44.795 --> 31:47.358
Like, God, I'm not hurting anybody when I hurt myself.

31:47.898 --> 31:50.701
So why does it matter if I do this, if it only impacts me?

31:50.741 --> 31:51.562
Maybe it's not that.

31:51.582 --> 31:54.484
Maybe your excuse instead is it's just not that big of a deal.

31:55.385 --> 31:56.506
Christians love this one.

31:57.567 --> 31:58.248
I'm not drunk.

31:59.309 --> 32:00.290
I'm just a little tipsy.

32:04.013 --> 32:04.754
Maybe it's not,

32:05.666 --> 32:31.602
that maybe instead it's God I'm staying sexually pure but part of the way that I pursue my personal purity is I've got a masturbate like how else am I going to get a sexual outlet God like I can't be single forever and if you're gonna call me to be single you're not gonna give me anybody to marry then I guess this is the only way that I'm gonna be able to process these sort of emotions maybe it's not that maybe it's God I'm not hurting my witness like it's not that big of a deal I'm not hurting my witness if everybody around me is saved oh my god

32:35.010 --> 32:43.499
We justify our sin, our indulgences, and our addiction all the time.

32:46.462 --> 32:50.187
Simply because it feels good to do bad things.

32:51.988 --> 32:53.590
You know what God has to say about that?

32:55.532 --> 32:59.577
He says, in Galatians 6, do not be deceived.

33:00.918 --> 33:01.619
I'm not mocked.

33:03.021 --> 33:04.402
For whatever one sows,

33:04.642 --> 33:06.324
That will he also reap?

33:07.125 --> 33:14.354
For the one who sows his own flesh will from the flesh reap corruption, but the one who sows to the spirit will from the spirit reap eternal life.

33:16.277 --> 33:17.218
What's that passage saying?

33:19.281 --> 33:21.103
It's saying you cultivate whatever you tolerate.

33:23.046 --> 33:24.668
You cultivate whatever you tolerate.

33:24.688 --> 33:26.690
It's like whatever sin it is you're tolerating.

33:27.031 --> 33:30.215
That is the sin that you're cultivating.

33:31.797 --> 33:32.818
So what are you tolerating?

33:34.434 --> 33:38.118
Maybe it seems harmless right now, but I guarantee you it will not be harmless later on.

33:39.480 --> 33:40.761
I remember talking to a friend of mine.

33:41.242 --> 33:44.285
It was right after I made the switch from college ministry and to young adult ministry.

33:44.345 --> 33:46.708
And he said something that really stuck with me.

33:46.808 --> 33:47.829
It resonated to this day.

33:47.849 --> 33:50.312
He was like, dude, young adult ministry is awesome.

33:50.332 --> 33:50.912
You're going to love it.

33:50.952 --> 33:51.913
It's amazing.

33:52.594 --> 33:53.996
But there's something you need to be aware of.

33:55.557 --> 33:58.941
In college ministry, you see the seeds of sin.

34:00.002 --> 34:03.346
But in young adult ministry, you see the fruit of sin.

34:04.194 --> 34:04.895
Why is that?

34:06.057 --> 34:13.128
Because if sin goes untamed, sin runs wild.

34:14.510 --> 34:21.521
It must be addressed, which is why I am pleading with you tonight to do something about it.

34:22.342 --> 34:30.034
Like I am begging you, don't just justify the struggle, mortify the struggle, put it to death, put it down.

34:30.562 --> 34:32.385
Nothing likes to die in this life.

34:32.425 --> 34:37.271
Your sin doesn't either, and yet I'm praying you would do something about it.

34:38.133 --> 34:39.655
Gosh, I'm praying you would do something about it.

34:39.695 --> 34:43.600
I'm running out of time, but I just feel the need to keep pushing into you.

34:43.820 --> 34:54.015
So not just indulge a bunch of religious activity, but to literally lean into the spiritual reality that you have an enemy.

34:54.035 --> 34:56.498
It doesn't want you to do well.

34:56.802 --> 34:58.525
He doesn't want you to experience life.

34:58.945 --> 35:00.668
He doesn't want you to find joy.

35:00.688 --> 35:08.980
And so he will bait you, lure you, take you into other places, promising you you'll find it there when in reality he knows it's not over there at all.

35:10.643 --> 35:12.926
Do something about it.

35:14.308 --> 35:15.610
Confess your sin.

35:16.552 --> 35:17.994
Get some friends.

35:18.695 --> 35:19.676
Wage war.

35:20.357 --> 35:21.900
Strengthen your weak knees.

35:22.461 --> 35:26.066
Like go to battle against that which is going to battle against you.

35:27.330 --> 35:29.413
because you're already promised the victory.

35:30.415 --> 35:33.119
You already know death is defeated.

35:35.843 --> 35:37.546
So why then would you fear?

35:39.048 --> 35:42.293
Go to work, kill that which is seeking to kill you.

35:43.434 --> 35:44.516
And you don't have to do it alone.

35:44.556 --> 35:48.763
David tells us that you get to do it alongside friends, which is where he goes in verse five.

35:48.783 --> 35:50.585
He says, let a righteous man strike me.

35:51.246 --> 35:51.907
It's a kindness.

35:52.488 --> 35:53.189
Let him rebuke me.

35:53.630 --> 35:54.551
It's oil for my head.

35:54.612 --> 35:56.274
Let my head not refuse it.

35:56.738 --> 36:03.149
The third step David gives us for controlling our cravings is you have to find friends who will correct you.

36:04.291 --> 36:07.155
You have to find friends who will correct you.

36:07.175 --> 36:10.080
He tells us two really important things about combating our cravings in this passage.

36:10.100 --> 36:13.366
He tells us, number one, you've got to find righteous friends.

36:13.666 --> 36:18.354
And number two, they need to interact with you in a righteous sort of way.

36:18.498 --> 36:20.561
When he says that they need to be righteous, what does that mean?

36:21.042 --> 36:26.811
Righteousness in the Bible is equivalent to godliness, which we talk about a lot today.

36:27.031 --> 36:32.640
So it isn't just someone that claims to know God, it's someone that is seeking to become like Him.

36:33.100 --> 36:37.928
That doesn't just say they've been saved by Jesus, but is seeking to become like Him.

36:37.988 --> 36:38.949
That's what you're looking for.

36:39.010 --> 36:43.116
You're looking for someone that is serious about pursuing holiness.

36:43.937 --> 36:44.879
Why do you want to find that?

36:45.339 --> 36:47.122
Someone that wants to be separate from their sin.

36:47.490 --> 36:53.119
Because if they're so serious about being separate from their sin, they're probably going to be helpful to helping you separate yourself from your own.

36:53.319 --> 36:53.860
That makes sense.

36:54.261 --> 36:57.486
When I showed up to Dallas, I did not have a barber.

36:57.947 --> 36:59.870
I desperately needed to find someone to cut my hair.

37:00.210 --> 37:01.011
And so what did I do?

37:01.532 --> 37:05.739
I looked across all the land for the best head of hair I could find.

37:06.760 --> 37:10.026
And when I found it, I asked that gentleman, where did he get your haircut?

37:10.967 --> 37:12.089
And he told me where he got his haircut.

37:12.369 --> 37:13.872
And that's now where I get my haircut to this day.

37:14.332 --> 37:15.314
Why did I do that?

37:15.874 --> 37:19.240
because there were signs of credibility in his life.

37:20.241 --> 37:23.767
And thus, I gave him dignity to speak into mine.

37:23.968 --> 37:24.929
Makes sense how that works.

37:25.230 --> 37:26.532
We do this in every area of life.

37:26.552 --> 37:27.173
You want to get fit.

37:27.213 --> 37:28.095
You look to someone that's fit.

37:28.275 --> 37:28.876
You want to get healthy.

37:28.896 --> 37:29.678
You look to someone that's healthy.

37:29.838 --> 37:30.399
You want to get smart.

37:30.419 --> 37:31.200
You look to someone that's smart.

37:31.421 --> 37:34.025
This is the way that we learn in life.

37:34.145 --> 37:39.314
If you want to combat your sin, you're going to need people that are serious about doing that themselves.

37:40.738 --> 37:42.380
He also tells us how we should interact.

37:42.420 --> 37:46.064
He tells us that we should interact in a way that's characterized by two different words.

37:46.424 --> 37:51.690
The first is he says they should strike him, which is a little off-putting.

37:51.810 --> 37:52.531
Can we just admit that?

37:52.811 --> 37:56.555
I don't know that I necessarily want a friend to strike me until you understand what the Hebrew means.

37:57.176 --> 38:02.582
The Hebrew tells us that it's the idea of someone speaking with decisive impact.

38:03.543 --> 38:09.970
So it would be the idea of when they speak, it's like they swing the hammer and thus they deal the blow.

38:10.306 --> 38:11.107
That's what you want.

38:11.247 --> 38:15.432
You want someone that when they speak, it makes a material difference in your life.

38:15.853 --> 38:16.974
That's not the only thing though.

38:17.414 --> 38:22.220
He says that he wants someone who will rebuke him, meaning someone that will gently admonish him or correct him.

38:22.260 --> 38:24.903
You want someone that can do both of these things.

38:25.925 --> 38:33.133
You see, you want people in your life who love you enough to tell you the things that you need to hear, not the things that you want to hear.

38:34.014 --> 38:37.298
In the Bible, it authenticates this kind of friendship.

38:37.986 --> 38:40.249
A few verses just so you can take my word for it.

38:40.269 --> 38:46.779
Proverbs 27, 6 says faithful or trusted are the wounds of a friend, the profuse or the kisses of an enemy.

38:47.681 --> 38:52.748
Proverbs 28, 23, whoever rebukes a man will afterward find more favor than he who flatters with his tongue.

38:53.409 --> 39:00.059
And then Jesus even said this in Revelation 3, 19 at the end of all time, he said, those whom I love, I reprove and I discipline.

39:00.841 --> 39:02.623
Isn't that interesting that that's what he says there?

39:02.864 --> 39:03.485
I reprove them.

39:03.745 --> 39:04.426
I discipline them.

39:04.646 --> 39:05.468
I love them.

39:05.728 --> 39:07.090
So be zealous and repent.

39:08.066 --> 39:11.609
I know these types of friendships have been some of the greatest gifts in my life.

39:11.649 --> 39:21.459
Like whenever I've been in seasons of particular hardship and thus struggle, my friends and I have come together and we have literally written questions.

39:21.539 --> 39:23.160
We want the others to ask us.

39:24.461 --> 39:25.262
Why do we do that?

39:26.964 --> 39:28.625
Because nobody knows me better than me.

39:28.665 --> 39:30.187
Minus my wife.

39:30.507 --> 39:31.988
But I know myself really well.

39:32.589 --> 39:35.171
I know where I go whenever I'm tempted.

39:35.612 --> 39:38.034
I know what I do whenever I'm bored.

39:38.146 --> 39:42.192
I know when I'm tired, what is my inclination?

39:42.272 --> 39:44.074
I know myself.

39:44.114 --> 39:53.087
And so rather than someone trying to ask any questions and investigate what's going on, what if I just handed them the appropriate list of questions to interrogate me thoroughly?

39:54.088 --> 39:55.670
That would be the wisest thing for me to do.

39:55.731 --> 40:06.866
That would be the wisest thing for all of us to do, to look to a friend that is again, godly, man, they are serious about pursuing Jesus and they're willing to speak

40:07.138 --> 40:08.220
Honestly with you.

40:10.082 --> 40:14.549
And so you give them the set of questions and you let them investigate your life.

40:14.950 --> 40:19.156
You have some risky conversations that are going to leave you exposed.

40:20.017 --> 40:21.600
Does it feel good to be exposed?

40:22.621 --> 40:22.962
No.

40:24.544 --> 40:28.390
But it is better to be exposed with a friend than safe in your sin.

40:28.450 --> 40:33.157
So you find someone who wants to get into the thick of it with you.

40:35.601 --> 40:36.402
You find

40:37.506 --> 40:39.429
the godliest friends you can.

40:40.991 --> 40:50.646
You hand them a list of questions, and you give them permission to ask you all of them at least once a week.

40:50.666 --> 40:51.627
It'll be what David says.

40:52.408 --> 40:54.111
It'll be the kindest thing they can do to you.

40:54.472 --> 40:55.753
It'll be like oil on your head.

40:55.773 --> 40:58.758
It'll be honoring to you for them to do these things.

40:59.459 --> 41:00.821
Okay, last thing, let's keep going.

41:01.021 --> 41:01.702
Verses 8 through 10.

41:03.806 --> 41:06.770
David says, but my eyes are toward you, oh God, my Lord.

41:07.554 --> 41:08.916
In you, I seek refuge.

41:09.696 --> 41:11.198
Leave me not defenseless.

41:11.939 --> 41:16.544
Keep me from the trap that they've laid for me, from the snares of evildoers.

41:17.405 --> 41:21.570
Let the wicked fall into their own nets while I pass by safely.

41:24.193 --> 41:30.319
The fourth and final step to controlling your cravings is you have to pursue intimacy with God.

41:32.222 --> 41:33.964
You have to pursue intimacy with God.

41:35.145 --> 41:36.146
By the end of this psalm,

41:39.170 --> 41:41.152
David's circumstances are not changed.

41:42.053 --> 41:47.579
Like he's not magically or miraculously pulled out of all the hardship that he's facing.

41:48.020 --> 41:50.983
Instead, he is still in the midst of it.

41:51.444 --> 41:58.612
But rather than be where he was at the beginning distracted by what everybody was doing, he's laser focused on what God is doing.

41:59.713 --> 42:00.774
He has set his gaze.

42:00.894 --> 42:04.898
I love the way it says, my eyes are toward you, O God.

42:06.480 --> 42:08.082
In you, I seek refuge.

42:11.330 --> 42:19.341
If you walk into a room and you see that what you want, you don't aimlessly move around.

42:20.983 --> 42:22.064
You're filled with purpose.

42:22.805 --> 42:24.648
And so you pursue wholeheartedly.

42:25.689 --> 42:26.550
That's what he's saying.

42:27.211 --> 42:29.334
Get your eyes on God.

42:30.315 --> 42:38.706
And as you do so, he'll take care of all the traps and all the snares and all the nets.

42:39.202 --> 42:41.405
What does it look like to get your eyes on God?

42:41.846 --> 42:46.913
I love the way that Thomas Chalmers who wrote the explosive power of new affection.

42:47.714 --> 42:48.294
He says this.

42:48.695 --> 42:54.163
He says, the best way to overcome the world is not with morality and self-discipline.

42:54.223 --> 42:55.324
Pull yourself up by your boot jokes.

42:55.685 --> 42:56.726
No.

42:56.746 --> 43:02.634
Christians overcome the world by seeing the beauty and the excellence of Christ.

43:03.495 --> 43:08.402
They overcome the world by seeing something more attractive than the world.

43:11.138 --> 43:16.024
So how do you see he who is most attractive of all?

43:16.645 --> 43:21.311
How do you set your eyes and fix your gaze to behold his beauty?

43:21.791 --> 43:23.453
I'll give you two ideas very quickly.

43:24.234 --> 43:28.499
Number one is you avoid unnecessary temptation.

43:29.280 --> 43:30.742
You avoid unnecessary temptation.

43:30.982 --> 43:36.429
James 1 14 tells us, but each person is tempted when he's lured in enticed by his own desires.

43:36.950 --> 43:38.371
I love the way that John Owen says it.

43:38.852 --> 43:40.434
He says, no.

43:40.578 --> 43:45.625
that he that dares to dally with occasions of sin will dare to sin.

43:46.427 --> 43:47.027
What's that mean?

43:47.668 --> 43:52.375
If you put yourself in a position to be tempted by sin, guess what's gonna happen?

43:53.557 --> 43:54.138
You're gonna sin.

43:55.300 --> 43:58.685
So avoid unnecessary temptation.

44:00.768 --> 44:07.858
Like if the gem or his cubicle or

44:08.226 --> 44:15.801
your run club or Netflix or your boyfriend's bedroom.

44:15.861 --> 44:16.743
I don't know what it is.

44:16.783 --> 44:26.482
Like if those places dare you to sin, if they tempt you to sin, don't go near them.

44:27.042 --> 44:30.887
And if you're in a spot where it's like, but I can't avoid those situations.

44:30.927 --> 44:32.870
I can't avoid those specific settings.

44:32.890 --> 44:33.330
Then guess what?

44:33.390 --> 44:34.572
You need to set some parameters.

44:34.772 --> 44:36.314
You need to put some rules on your life.

44:36.515 --> 44:39.499
You need to literally regulate your behavior.

44:39.579 --> 44:41.401
You treat yourself like a child.

44:41.481 --> 44:42.423
What do you do with children?

44:42.623 --> 44:48.170
You tell them what they can and they cannot do and you hold them fast to it and you get some people around you that will hold you fast to it as well.

44:49.392 --> 44:52.716
One of the best things that ever happened to me was a group of friends in my life.

44:52.776 --> 44:57.042
They would ground me if ever I went against the parameters that I set.

44:57.762 --> 44:58.743
Isn't that ridiculous?

44:59.685 --> 45:00.686
How do you think you are?

45:00.726 --> 45:01.828
You think you can ground me?

45:01.868 --> 45:03.290
Yeah, man, you gave us permission too.

45:03.650 --> 45:04.031
Fair enough.

45:04.311 --> 45:10.439
You know, like you need some people that are willing to look at you, love you, and ground you from doing that what you should not do.

45:12.803 --> 45:18.911
You need some people that are willing to go the distance when you're not willing to go.

45:20.153 --> 45:22.496
You gotta avoid unnecessary temptation.

45:22.516 --> 45:26.802
And secondly, you gotta pursue personal proximity.

45:28.194 --> 45:33.099
Like you've got to take out the bad and you've got to replace it with good.

45:33.880 --> 45:35.262
You got to seek Jesus.

45:36.323 --> 45:42.730
And I know as I'm saying all this, you're like, wow, that's all very profound.

45:44.752 --> 45:47.054
You don't need more complicated truth.

45:51.740 --> 45:56.204
You just need to apply basic truth.

45:56.224 --> 45:57.746
And basic truth says,

45:58.114 --> 46:09.385
Get your eyes off the things that tempt you to sin and get your eyes on the one who has saved you from sin.

46:09.405 --> 46:11.647
Pursue personal proximity.

46:11.667 --> 46:14.690
That doesn't mean do a bunch of religious activity.

46:14.750 --> 46:17.372
That means get close to Jesus.

46:17.873 --> 46:21.256
Do the things that bring you near to Him.

46:21.316 --> 46:27.282
David says in Psalm 27, four, one thing have I asked,

46:27.362 --> 46:35.114
That will I seek, that I might gaze upon the beauty of the Lord, to enquire in His temple.

46:37.578 --> 46:45.810
All David wants is to see Jesus in seek after him, because he knows there's no one like that man, there's no one

46:45.954 --> 46:49.722
that there's no one that comes relatively close in comparison.

46:50.062 --> 46:53.910
I have seen in my God that which cannot be seen anywhere else.

46:53.930 --> 46:57.498
And so I'm gonna do everything in my power to get as close to him as I can.

46:57.558 --> 46:59.602
For the sake of time,

47:00.610 --> 47:04.074
I can't deeply unpack for you how you do that.

47:04.154 --> 47:05.315
How do you get close to them?

47:05.355 --> 47:06.577
You can take some guesses.

47:06.657 --> 47:12.243
It's going to mean you're going to read the scripture, you're going to pray to God, you're going to confess your sin, you're going to get involved in community.

47:12.263 --> 47:15.427
But if you want to unpack all that, we're going to have some people down front that would love to do it with you.

47:15.667 --> 47:17.650
But there's nothing more important than this.

47:18.511 --> 47:21.274
You pursue him because he pursued you.

47:22.015 --> 47:24.818
Like when none of us trusted God, he trusted God.

47:25.090 --> 47:27.315
He trusted God with his whole life.

47:27.396 --> 47:36.157
When none of us could be justified in our sin, because we were all justifying our sin, he stepped into the story and he justified us of our sin anyways.

47:38.021 --> 47:41.810
When all of us could not remain correct, he came.

47:41.986 --> 47:44.451
And he walked correctly in this life.

47:44.872 --> 47:50.042
And yet he died our death, absorbing into himself all the wrath of God intended for us.

47:50.542 --> 47:54.851
And yet because he wanted intimacy with you and me, he burst forth from the grave.

47:55.211 --> 48:00.442
He rose from the dead that any that would place every to him might have relationship with him forever.

48:01.764 --> 48:02.806
Why do you pursue him?

48:03.788 --> 48:04.850
Because he pursued you.

48:05.346 --> 48:09.811
He came to save you from that, which you feel like you cannot be saved from.

48:09.831 --> 48:13.514
He came to free you from that, which you feel so enslaved to.

48:13.554 --> 48:21.883
He came to rescue you from that, which you feel like has reigned in your life for far too long.

48:21.903 --> 48:28.309
Come to Him, place your faith in Him, and live a new life beginning tonight.

48:28.329 --> 48:29.250
Let me pray that you would.

48:30.131 --> 48:32.754
And Jesus, thank you for this evening,

48:33.922 --> 48:35.325
Thank you, God, for these people.

48:35.385 --> 48:36.908
Thank you, God, for your word.

48:38.932 --> 48:40.395
Thank you, God, that this is real.

48:41.276 --> 48:45.064
Gosh.

48:45.084 --> 48:48.370
You and I have just been wrestling all day long.

48:48.930 --> 48:52.916
that I don't God want the porch to be a place where we just do really good ministry, God.

48:52.976 --> 49:00.066
No, I want the porch to be a place where there's power and there's impact and there's meaning and there's purpose, God.

49:00.226 --> 49:07.116
I need the porch to be a place where the porch's name is not what's remembered, but it's Jesus' name that is remembered, God.

49:07.276 --> 49:16.850
I want this to be a place where heaven touches down to earth, where we feel a transcendent collision, God, where the supernatural and natural collide into one.

49:17.026 --> 49:22.651
We're Jesus, we get to behold you as you are, not as we think you to be, but as you are.

49:23.893 --> 49:25.174
It's O God, police.

49:28.777 --> 49:32.281
Let these next moments matter.

49:37.285 --> 49:39.307
God, you could wash away the whole ministry.

49:39.367 --> 49:41.690
You could take away all of the porch.

49:42.450 --> 49:46.194
But I'm praying, God, you would save these people forever.

49:49.058 --> 49:52.724
that you would give them eyes to see that which is most beautiful.

49:53.245 --> 49:57.551
And you would do that starting now.

49:57.571 --> 49:58.533
We sing to you, Jesus.

49:58.893 --> 49:59.815
We need you, Jesus.

50:00.436 --> 50:02.379
And we're going to respond to you, Jesus.

50:04.742 --> 50:05.644
That's in your name we pray.

50:06.645 --> 50:07.026
Amen.

